        public Request(Request.Method method,
               java.lang.String url,
               Response.Listener<T> listener)
        Creates a new request with the given method (one of the values from Request.Method), URL, and error listener. Note that the normal response listener is not provided here as delivery of responses is provided by subclasses, who have a better idea of how to deliver an already-parsed response.
        Parameters:
        method - A Request.Method
        url - An url
        listener - A callback listener

      • putParameters

        public Request putParameters(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> query)
        Add request parameters to this request. The parameters will be appended as HTTP query parameters to the URL, when the SDK executes the request. Therefore you should not do nested structures, only simple key-value-pairs. This is not the same as appending a body to the request, when doing a PUT or POST request.
        Parameters:
        query - A map of parameters to bundle along with this request
        Returns:
        this object

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Returns a complete printable representation of this Request, e.g: GET: https://api.etilbudsavis.dk/v2/catalogs/{catalog_id}?param1=value1&param2=value2

        The SDK/API parameters are not added to the getParameters() query parameters}, before the request is handed to the RequestQueue. So if you want to have the SDK/API parameters appended as well in the string do:

        ShopGun.getInstance().add(Request)

        and then call:

        toString()
        Overrides:
        toString in class java.lang.Object
